./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:1:# Planner: Recognize `external` Side-Effect + `send_mail` Output Type — Implementation Plan
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:5:**Goal:** Make `send_mail` selectable by `plan_chain()` as a terminal chain hop by (1) teaching `_slug_side_effect()` to recognize `side_effect='external'` instead of coercing it to `unknown`, and (2) backfilling `send_mail`'s empty `output_types` to `'text'` in the live registry.
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:17:This plan implements **only** what `US-CLIREG-PLANNER-SIDEEFFECT-VOCAB-01`'s narrowed spec covers: the `external` vocabulary gap (Bug 1) and `send_mail`'s empty `output_types` (Bug 2). It explicitly does **not** touch:
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:30:| `~/.hermes/cli-registry.db` | Live SQLite registry (not a repo file) | Single-row `UPDATE`: `send_mail.output_types` `'' → 'text'` |
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:151:- The 3 new tests use synthetic `emid`/`mid` slugs with nonempty `output_types`, not `send_mail` itself — this correctly isolates Bug 1 (side-effect recognition) from Bug 2 (empty output_types), per the spec's Testing section. Chunk 2 handles the real `send_mail` row.
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:158:## Chunk 2: Data fix — backfill `send_mail`'s `output_types`
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:169:sqlite3 ~/.hermes/cli-registry.db "SELECT cli_slug, input_types, output_types, side_effect, confidence FROM capability WHERE cli_slug='send_mail';"
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:172:Expected output: `send_mail|text||external|declared` (empty `output_types` field between the two `|` characters). If this doesn't match — STOP, the live data has drifted since the spec was written; re-verify against current spec assumptions before proceeding.
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:181:Expected: exactly one row, `send_mail`. This confirms the spec's "scoped to exactly one row" claim still holds.
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:199:sqlite3 ~/.hermes/cli-registry.db "UPDATE capability SET output_types='text' WHERE cli_slug='send_mail' AND output_types='';"
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:208:Expected: `1`. If `0`, the `WHERE` clause matched nothing (row already changed or slug/condition mismatch) — investigate before re-running. If `>1` — STOP immediately, this should be impossible given `cli_slug` is not unique-constrained but the live registry should have at most one `send_mail` capability row; investigate before proceeding further.
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:213:sqlite3 ~/.hermes/cli-registry.db "SELECT cli_slug, input_types, output_types, side_effect, confidence FROM capability WHERE cli_slug='send_mail';"
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:216:Expected: `send_mail|text|text|external|declared`.
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:226:- The `WHERE output_types=''` clause (not just `WHERE cli_slug='send_mail'`) makes the UPDATE idempotent-safe — re-running it after success is a no-op (`changes()` → 0), not a silent overwrite of some other manual edit.
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:234:### Task 5: Prove `send_mail` is selectable in an isolated/scoped simulation
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:239:- [ ] **Step 1: Run an isolated-DB simulation against the real send_mail row**
./docs/plans/2026-07-12-planner-external-side-effect.md:241:This reproduces the spec's own post-panel Codex verification. Use a throwaway copy of the live DB filtered to just the `send_mail` row plus its dependencies, or run against the full live DB with `max_candidate_chains` raised (per AC-05's explicit allowance for either isolated-subset OR raised-cap verification):
